HAPPINESS
  Civilian morale.  Low happiness causes unrest and reduces productivity.
  High happiness improves combat performance.

HAPPINESS REQUIREMENT
  As your technology and education advance, your citizens expect a
  matching quality of life.  The happiness they "require" is:

    hap_req = (tech - 40) / 40 + education / 3

  Examples:
    tech=0,   edu=0:   hap_req = -1.0   (no requirement at game start)
    tech=40,  edu=0:   hap_req =  0.0
    tech=80,  edu=0:   hap_req =  1.0
    tech=80,  edu=6:   hap_req =  3.0
    tech=120, edu=15:  hap_req =  7.0
    tech=160, edu=30:  hap_req = 13.0

  Early game the requirement is negative, so you can ignore happiness
  until tech passes about 40 AND education starts climbing.  After
  that, hap_req rises fast — build parks BEFORE you need them.

EFFECTS OF LOW HAPPINESS
  Each update, for every sector you own:
    If your happiness < hap_req, there is a chance of loyalty damage:
      chance = (hap_req - happiness) / 5.0

  When loyalty is damaged (loyal > 65) and mil < civ/20:
    - Sector work rate (sct_work) drops — civilians refuse to work
    - Small chance (~7% max) of REVOLT: sector abandons your nation
    - You receive a telegram: "Civil unrest in <sector>!"

  At very high loyalty (> 100), work rate can drop to zero.
  Your sectors produce nothing.  This is a game-ending spiral:
  no production -> can't build -> loyalty keeps rising -> more revolts.

  Rule of thumb: keep happiness at or above hap_req at all times.

EFFECTS OF HIGH HAPPINESS
  Happiness also affects COMBAT.  The ratio of your happiness to your
  opponent's modifies combat effectiveness:

    combat_factor = your_hap / their_hap   (clamped: 0.8 to 2.0)

  Examples:
    your_hap = 2x opponent:  +100% fighting effectiveness
    your_hap = same:          no modifier
    your_hap = half:          -20% fighting effectiveness

  A well-happy army fights much better.  Raiding nations with low
  happiness is much easier.

RAISING HAPPINESS
  Build parks (p sectors):
    Consumes: 1 LCM per unit produced
    Requires: no level — build from day one
    Happiness is a fast moving average (window ~120 ETU at default 60 ETU/update)
    It responds twice as fast as education.

  Educated populations need more parks.  The happiness your parks
  produce is multiplied by:
    hap_edu = 1.5 - (education + 10) / (education + 20)

    edu=0:   1.00 (baseline)
    edu=10:  0.83
    edu=30:  0.70
    edu=60:  0.61
    edu=100: 0.58

  At edu=100 you need roughly twice as many parks to produce the
  same happiness as at edu=0.  Plan LCM production accordingly.

MONITORING HAPPINESS
  Use 'nation' to check your current happiness vs. hap_req:
    nation        — shows Education, Happiness, Technology, Research

  Each update report also shows the delta (change this update).
  If happiness is dropping, add more parks immediately.

STAYING AHEAD
  1. Build 1-2 parks early — LCM is cheap and parks pay off fast
  2. Watch tech and education — when tech > 40 and edu > 3,
     hap_req starts climbing
  3. If you see "Civil unrest" telegrams, add parks NOW
  4. More civs = more LCM consumed by parks (1 LCM per park unit)
     Scale your LCM production with population growth

